        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID24",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Dear participant, You will be taking part in the Machine speech, human speech project conducted b...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Dear participant,<br>\n<br>\nYou will be taking part in the <i>Machine speech, human speech</i> project conducted by Raya Mezeklieva under the supervision of Fausto Carcassi and Giorgio Sbardolini from the Institute of Logic, Language and Computation (ILLC) of the University of Amsterdam.<br>\n<br>\n<b>Purpose of the research project </b><br>\nLarge language models (LLMs) can generate text that is almost indistinguishable from human writing. Given the increasing popularity and availability of these systems, people\u2019s skepticism towards the authenticity of written content intensifies. This research aims to find out how people may modify written text to signal human authorship and distinguish it from LLM-generated content.&nbsp;<br>\n<br>\n<b>Who can take part in this research? </b><br>\nWe are inviting adult native speakers of the English language to take part in this research.&nbsp;Before the experiment begins, we will verify you match this profile.<br>\n<br>\n<b>Instructions and procedure </b><br>\nThe experiment will start with a few questions regarding your background and your experience with LLMs (~3 minutes). During the main task, you will read two texts, then you will edit a third text with the goal of distinguishing its writing style from the texts you will have just read. Each text will contain approximately 200 words. After you have submitted your modifications, you will be asked to explain your reasoning. At the end of the experiment, you will be debriefed about your experience and the purpose of this study (~3 minutes). The total duration of the experiment will be approximately 20 minutes.\n\n<br>\nYou are not allowed to use any generative artificial intelligence tools or external assistance during any part of the experiment. This includes, but is not limited to, text-generating systems, automated writing tools, or paraphrasing software.<br>\n<br>\n<b>Voluntary participation &amp; risks </b><br>\nYou will be participating in this research on a voluntary basis. This means you are free to stop taking part at any stage without consequences or penalty. If you decide to stop or withdraw your consent, all the information gathered up until then will be permanently deleted. This research has no known risks.<br>\n<br>\n<b>Privacy </b><br>\nThe information gathered will be used for the master\u2019s thesis of Raya Mezeklieva, which will be published on the <a href=\"https://msclogic.illc.uva.nl/theses/recent/\">ILLC website</a>. Any other potential publication for which the data could be used will be in scientific journals only. Fully anonymized data may be available online in tandem with these scientific publications. We guarantee that you will remain anonymous under all circumstances. Your personal information will not be viewed by third parties. Participants can request more information from the researcher at any time about their rights as data subjects under the EU privacy law, the GDPR.<br>\n<br>\n<b>Further Information</b><br>\nFor further information, please contact Raya Mezeklieva (<a href=\"mailto:raya.mezeklieva@student.uva.nl\">raya.mezeklieva@student.uva.nl</a>), Fausto Carcassi (<a href=\"mailto:f.carcassi@uva.nl\">f.carcassi@uva.nl</a>), or Giorgio Sbardolini (<a href=\"mailto:g.sbardolini@uva.nl\">g.sbardolini@uva.nl</a>). If you have any complaints regarding this project, you can contact the Secretary of the Ethics Committee of the Faculty of Humanities of the University of Amsterdam (<a href=\"mailto:commissie-ethiek-fgw@uva.nl\">commissie-ethiek-fgw@uva.nl</a>).",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "consent_info",
                "QuestionType": "DB",
                "Selector": "TB",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Dear participant, You will be taking part in the Machine speech, human speech project conducted b...",
                "ChoiceOrder": [],
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionID": "QID24",
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Dear participant,<br />\n<br />\nYou will be taking part in the <i>Machine speech, human speech</i> project conducted by Raya Mezeklieva under the supervision of Fausto Carcassi and Giorgio Sbardolini from the Institute of Logic, Language and Computation (ILLC) of the University of Amsterdam.<br />\n<br />\n<b>Purpose of the research project </b><br />\nLarge language models (LLMs) can generate text that is almost indistinguishable from human writing. Given the increasing popularity and availability of these systems, people&rsquo;s skepticism towards the authenticity of written content intensifies. This research aims to find out how people may modify written text to signal human authorship and distinguish it from LLM-generated content.&nbsp;<br />\n<br />\n<b>Who can take part in this research? </b><br />\nWe are inviting adult native speakers of the English language to take part in this research.&nbsp;Before the experiment begins, we will verify you match this profile.<br />\n<br />\n<b>Instructions and procedure </b><br />\nThe experiment will start with a few questions regarding your background and your experience with LLMs. During the main task, you will read three texts, then you will edit a fourth text with the goal of distinguishing its writing style from the texts you will have just read. Each text will contain approximately 200 words. After you have submitted your modifications, you will be asked to explain your reasoning. At the end of the experiment, you will be debriefed about your experience and the purpose of this study. The total duration of the experiment will be 20-30 minutes.<br />\n<br />\nYou are not allowed to use any generative artificial intelligence tools or external assistance during any part of the experiment. This includes, but is not limited to, text-generating systems, automated writing tools, or paraphrasing software.<br />\n<br />\n<b>Voluntary participation &amp; risks </b><br />\nYou will be participating in this research on a voluntary basis. This means you are free to stop taking part at any stage without consequences or penalty. If you decide to stop or withdraw your consent, all the information gathered up until then will be permanently deleted. This research has no known risks.<br />\n<br />\n<b>Privacy </b><br />\nThe information gathered will be used for the master&rsquo;s thesis of Raya Mezeklieva, which will be published on the <a href=\"https://msclogic.illc.uva.nl/theses/recent/\">ILLC website</a>. Any other potential publication for which the data could be used will be in scientific journals only. Fully anonymized data may be available online in tandem with these scientific publications. We guarantee that you will remain anonymous under all circumstances. Your personal information will not be viewed by third parties. Participants can request more information from the researcher at any time about their rights as data subjects under the EU privacy law, the GDPR.<br />\n<br />\n<b>Further Information</b><br />\nFor further information, please contact Raya Mezeklieva (<a href=\"mailto:raya.mezeklieva@student.uva.nl\">raya.mezeklieva@student.uva.nl</a>), Fausto Carcassi (<a href=\"mailto:f.carcassi@uva.nl\">f.carcassi@uva.nl</a>), or Giorgio Sbardolini (<a href=\"mailto:g.sbardolini@uva.nl\">g.sbardolini@uva.nl</a>). If you have any complaints regarding this project, you can contact the Secretary of the Ethics Committee of the Faculty of Humanities of the University of Amsterdam (<a href=\"mailto:commissie-ethiek-fgw@uva.nl\">commissie-ethiek-fgw@uva.nl</a>)."
            }
        },
