                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>The Nobel Peace Prize was awarded today to the International Campaign for Nuclear Abolition, honoring its decades-long effort to eliminate atomic weapons and reduce the risk of catastrophic war. The Norwegian Nobel Committee praised the coalition of grassroots activists, scientists, and survivors of nuclear testing for building global momentum behind the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons. In its citation, the committee said the group had \"reframed the debate on nuclear deterrence by highlighting the humanitarian consequences of any use.\"</p>\n           <p>Accepting the award in Oslo, executive director Maria Santos called the prize \"a tribute to ordinary people who refuse to live under the shadow of annihilation.\" She urged nuclear-armed states to join disarmament talks and invest instead in health, climate, and education. Leaders from several countries welcomed the decision, while officials in nuclear powers cautioned that deterrence remains essential to national security.</p>\n           <p>Analysts said the prize could intensify diplomatic pressure ahead of next year's nonproliferation review conference, where divisions between nuclear and non-nuclear states are expected. Founded in 2007, the campaign now includes more than 600 partner organizations worldwide and has focused on survivor testimony and youth activism. Committee chair Anne Lunde said the honor recognizes \"persistent moral leadership.\"</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Egypt's parliament has approved a long-debated agreement transferring sovereignty over two Red Sea islands, Tiran and Sanafir, to Saudi Arabia, marking a significant step in a controversial maritime deal. Lawmakers voted in favor of the accord during a plenary session, despite vocal opposition from some MPs and public protests in recent years.</p>\n           <p>The government has argued that the islands historically belong to Saudi Arabia and that the agreement corrects administrative arrangements dating back to the 1950s. Officials said the transfer would strengthen bilateral ties and unlock economic cooperation, including planned development projects in the Red Sea.</p>\n           <p>Critics, however, contend that the islands are Egyptian territory and have challenged the move in court. Previous judicial rulings had produced conflicting decisions, fueling a heated national debate over sovereignty and transparency. Security officials emphasized that navigation through the strategic Strait of Tiran will remain open in accordance with international agreements.</p>\n           <p>Saudi authorities welcomed the vote, describing it as a reaffirmation of historic rights and regional partnership. The agreement now awaits final ratification procedures, after which administrative control is expected to be formally transferred.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say the decision could reshape regional alliances and test domestic political stability in the months ahead. Across the region.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Jimmy Wales, cofounder of Wikipedia, says the online encyclopedia he helped launch 25 years ago needs a radical overhaul \u2014 and he believes blockchain technology could provide it. Speaking at a technology conference this week, Wales argued that Wikipedia\u2019s volunteer-driven model has struggled with declining editor participation, opaque governance disputes and growing mistrust over content moderation.</p>\n           <p>Under his proposal, articles and edits would be recorded on a public blockchain, creating a transparent, tamper-resistant history of every contribution. Contributors could earn digital tokens for verified edits, potentially providing financial incentives to attract subject-matter experts. Smart contracts might also be used to manage disputes and automate editorial decisions according to community-approved rules.</p>\n           <p>Wales contends that decentralization would reduce the power of small administrator groups and make it harder for coordinated misinformation campaigns to manipulate entries. Critics, however, question whether blockchain systems can scale to handle Wikipedia\u2019s vast traffic and warn that token incentives could encourage low-quality edits.</p>\n           <p>The Wikimedia Foundation said it is reviewing emerging technologies but remains committed to its nonprofit mission and community governance. Whether blockchain can truly replace Wikipedia\u2019s current infrastructure remains uncertain, yet the debate underscores mounting pressure to reinvent one of the internet\u2019s most trusted resources globally.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691461",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an\neditable text box prefilled with that sentence.\nMake any changes you think will help the text read convincingly as\nhuman-written and unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated. You may rephrase,\nadd, or remove content as you see fit. If you choose to merge sentences, enter\nthe combined version in the first relevant text box and leave the following\none(s) empty. You can also split sentences by writing multiple sentences within\na single text box. Edit as many text boxes as you feel are needed.\n<br /><br />",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "edit_c3",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691461",
                "QuestionType": "TE",
                "Selector": "ML",
                "DataVisibility": {
