                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Scientists have unveiled a newly discovered prehistoric worm-like creature they describe as \u201cstrange beyond measure,\u201d shedding light on an unusual branch of early animal evolution. The fossilized remains, found in 520\u2011million\u2011year\u2011old marine sediments in western China, reveal a soft-bodied organism with a tubular form, ringed segments, and a circular mouth lined with sharp, backward-facing spines.</p>\n           <p>Measuring just a few inches long, the creature likely lived on the seafloor during the Cambrian Period, a time when complex life rapidly diversified. Researchers believe it used its spiny mouth to latch onto prey or organic debris, drawing food into a simple digestive tract. Despite its modest size, the worm\u2019s anatomy is unlike that of any modern species.</p>\n           <p>\u201cIt\u2019s strange beyond measure,\u201d said lead paleontologist Dr. Li Wen. \u201cIts combination of features doesn\u2019t neatly fit into any known group, living or extinct.\u201d Advanced imaging techniques revealed preserved muscle fibers and traces of internal organs, offering rare insight into soft-bodied animals that seldom fossilize.</p>\n           <p>The discovery suggests that early marine ecosystems were more diverse and experimental than previously understood. Scientists hope further study will clarify where the enigmatic creature fits on the evolutionary tree and what it reveals about the origins of complex animals.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Skywatchers around the world are preparing for one of nature\u2019s most breathtaking events: a solar eclipse. But how much do you really know about this celestial phenomenon?</p>\n           <p>A solar eclipse occurs when the Moon passes between the Earth and the Sun, temporarily blocking some or all of the Sun\u2019s light. There are three main types: total, partial, and annular. During a total solar eclipse, the Moon completely covers the Sun, turning day into twilight for a few dramatic minutes. In a partial eclipse, only part of the Sun is obscured. An annular eclipse happens when the Moon is too far from Earth to fully cover the Sun, leaving a bright \u201cring of fire\u201d visible in the sky.</p>\n           <p>Solar eclipses do not happen every month because the Moon\u2019s orbit is slightly tilted relative to Earth\u2019s orbit around the Sun. When conditions align perfectly, the spectacle can be seen from specific regions of the world.</p>\n           <p>Experts warn that looking directly at a solar eclipse without proper eye protection can cause serious eye damage. Special eclipse glasses or indirect viewing methods are essential.</p>\n           <p>Beyond their beauty, solar eclipses help scientists study the Sun\u2019s outer atmosphere, known as the corona, offering valuable insights into solar activity and space weather.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Scientists have identified 91 previously unknown volcanoes buried deep beneath the Antarctic Ice Sheet, dramatically reshaping understanding of the frozen continent\u2019s geology. The discoveries, made using ice-penetrating radar and satellite data, reveal a vast volcanic province stretching across West Antarctica, with peaks ranging from 100 meters to nearly 4,000 meters in height.</p>\n           <p>Researchers say the hidden chain rivals some of the world\u2019s most active volcanic regions in scale, though it remains unclear how many of the volcanoes are dormant or potentially active. Most are concealed beneath up to two kilometers of ice, making direct observation impossible without advanced imaging technology.</p>\n           <p>The findings raise important questions about the stability of the Antarctic Ice Sheet. Scientists warn that geothermal heat from volcanic activity could accelerate melting from below, potentially influencing global sea level rise. However, experts caution that more research is needed to determine whether any of the volcanoes pose an immediate threat.</p>\n           <p>The discovery also offers new insight into Antarctica\u2019s tectonic history, suggesting the region may be more geologically dynamic than previously believed. Researchers plan further surveys to map the area in greater detail and assess how subglacial volcanic systems interact with the ice above.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691494",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an\neditable text box prefilled with that sentence.\nMake any changes you think will help the text read convincingly as\nhuman-written and unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated. You may rephrase,\nadd, or remove content as you see fit. If you choose to merge sentences, enter\nthe combined version in the first relevant text box and leave the following\none(s) empty. You can also split sentences by writing multiple sentences within\na single text box. Edit as many text boxes as you feel are needed.\n<br /><br />",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "edit_c14",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691494",
                "QuestionType": "TE",
                "Selector": "ML",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "ForceResponse": "OFF",
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
